<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Detailed posts from Alan VanCouvering</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=291504" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/036950.html">Please be patient over the next few days…</a></B><P>

<I>Please be patient with us over the next few days. As Velious goes live we are expecting to be very busy, both on the servers and with tech support. We will be doing everything we can to keep things running smoothly for everyone. But if something untoward happens, please understand that our staff will be working hard to help you out. We are anticipating a rather large increase in volume on the servers, in petitions and on our tech support phone lines. Velious is an exciting new adventure for everyone, with people rushing out to see the new lands. Servers will probably see a lot more activity than they are used to, and they already see a lot. So will our customer support personnel. Please, be patient with them during this busy time.<P>

And happy holidays to everyone!<P>

Alan</I><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/035745.html">Mage Issues, Take 2 ... Please Post No Flames</a></B><P>

<B>I'm sorry it took me so long to respond to this post. It's taken me three days just to write this response. It's been pretty busy in here…</B><P>

"Sword of Runes"<P>

<B>Thanks for seeing that as a fix. I do. :)</B><P>


"Call of the Hero<P>

However, Verant has said that the aggro will not be cleared all the time. This has interesting effects:<P>

1) The groupmate will be pulled out of the situation, but likely still in danger. Since the groupmate may still be on the hate list, the mob may give chase or summon the groupmate back."<P>

<B>Yup</B><P>

"2) The mage and groupmate can use CoH to pull a mob they otherwise could not pull.<P>

It's this last one that's interesting to me. Does Verant realize that this change will give groups with CoH-equipped mages the ability to pull big mobs more easily? I think clearing the hate list is the right thing to do. The mob believes the player to have gated, unless the summoned player is within the normal aggro range of the mob."<P>

<B>Well, it could be used that way, I suppose. But the chance of the hate list not being cleared is supposed to be pretty low… it might be faster to pull it the normal way.</B><P>

"And thanks for fixing the pet suicide!"<P>

<B>For you, anything. :)</B><P>

"Spell Skill Class<BR>
-----------------<BR>
I see Verant continuing the evocation path with magicians. This is disheartening. We are conjurers. Let the wizards have their evocation. Long ago I asked GZ why spells like "Rain of Spikes" were evocation. His answer? Paraphrase: "It was likely a mistake, but we can't change it now since people may have based their specialization on it being evocation." Sigh, I went to magician school. Mages should conjure heavy and sharp flying objects rather than rely on fire so heavily IMHO. Why are so many of our spells (with Kunark and current Velious spells) fire-based?"<P>

<B>Umm… I dunno? I'm, again, not really going to comment about Velious spells. But from reading the – oh so excellent – Prima Strat Guide, it does suggest that magicians should either specialize in conjuration or in evocation, and that many mages choose evocation.<P>

Is that really how it should be? I dunno. But GZ is right about it being a little late to change horses mid-stream. I'll mention this comment to the folks here and let them think about it, though for whatever is in Velious it's likely too late to fiddle with that.</B><P>

"Rain Spells<BR>
------------<BR>
Why do things that can't be affected by these spells reduce their effectiveness? I'm a magician...I'm going to have a pet up nearly all the time. Why is it that the rain loses a wave to my pet when my pet can't be harmed by the rain? Our rain spells are efficient only when all waves have a chance to hit. We pay for that efficiency with a resistance check on each wave and the risks of aggroing more mobs with its AE nature. Totally losing a wave on our pet makes these spells mana inefficient and is one of the main reasons they are not more heavily used. If you can't "fix" the pet problem, would you consider making the rain spells target only rather than AE? Again, the resistance checks on each wave should balance the spells."<P>

<B>It's just as easy to argue the other way, that pets should be damaged because they are obviously being hit by the spell…<P>

The real way to look at this is from the game mechanic point of view. Is having the pet take a wave making the spell too weak? Would making him not hit make the spell too strong? Honestly, I don't know. I do plan to bring this up, but probably not until after the holidays. I know that's not fast enough, but it's as fast as it's gonna happen. Verant deserves a holiday too…</B><P>

"PBAoE<BR>
-----<BR>
Thanks for Scintilation! I love frying those undead lowbies that think they can gang up and melee me into the ground. This spell isn't useful for things my level, but if it were, it'd overpower the class."<P>

<B>Cool. Thanks.</B><P>

"DOT Spells<BR>
----------<BR>
I know, you won't talk about Velious...But with the CD gold and the release around the corner, I thought you might speak a little more on the tpoc. Why are we getting weak DOTs? I'm not a shaman or necro. I don't want to waste mana and time on a DOT when I could do the same or more damage instantly. <P>

The tradeoff for DOTs is typically more damage, for more time. More time, same damage makes no sense to me. Shamans can debuff a mob to lengthen the fight, giving their DOT time to work. Necros can fear a mob, giving their DOT time to work. Magicians have no means of lengthening a fight other than to cast more slowly. In fact, the longer a fight continues, the worse shape magicians are in, typically. <P>

Please, reconsider DOTs...or make them more powerful for the trade off of time."<P>

<B>Umm… Let's wait on this. I'm really, really not talking about Velious stuff.</B><P>

"Fun Spells<BR>
----------<BR>
Bristlebane's Bundle...ah...what a fun spell! Seriously, having a summoned party pack is great! (You'd be surprised how many high levels I've tricked into spinning themselves with the bottle, heh). A few Velious spells like this would be great! In fact, as the DOTs are currently listed, take them all away. Give us things we can have fun with...Voice Graft, anyone?"<P>

<B>I'm all for fun spells too. I'm one of those people that tends to buy the fun spells first and worry about combat spells later. Eye of Zomm rocks! Again, I'll make this suggestion to the team, but it's probably too late to make any changes to Velious (I know, it might not have been when you first posted…)</B><P>

"Pet Graphics<BR>
------------<BR>
Rage of Zomm: Make it an eye...please? It would be something different to look at that fits the Zomm line. We can't hand the Rage weapons anyway, so why make it an elemental? Eyes are in the global file already, right?"<P>

<B>Very good idea.</B><P>

"High Level Elementals: We were told that there was no room in the global file. Sorry, mages. Spectres yes, new elementals no. Ok, fine. Now there's 3 more gods in the global file that I have yet to see in game. I guess gods have to be able to go to any zone. Ok, fine. Sigh."<P>

<B>Also a nice idea. I have no idea how much space there is (or isn't) for new globals. I do know that enchanters want some new stuff too. Both ideas are on my list.</B><BR><BR>

"Linkdeath<BR>
---------<BR>
Absor was incorrect in stating that it has always been the way it is now. In fact, it was changed when it was discovered that people were banking summoned arrows and food...or forcing linkdeath to save it (oh my!). I do not believe that I should be able to summon the equivalent of dragon loot (a Treasure Hunter's Satchel, for example). But really, did a few banked summoned items throw off the game balance?<BR><BR>

My inference is that Verant would rather punish all magicians and shaman 100% of the time than risk a few percent of players who are willing to linkdeath themselves to save summoned items. Isn't there a solution that meets both ends? You've already prevented summoned items from being banked. Put code into the /q and camp commands that trashes summoned items in a player's inventory and leave it at that. If someone is willing to physically disconnect a wire or reboot their machine in the middle of an EQ session to save some arrows, let them! Or consider this option: make it a 10% chance that things will poof on linkdeath...that will prevent people from using the summoned bags to lug around all their good loot, yet give us a fair shot at keeping our items most of the time."<BR><BR>

<B>There have been several suggestions for changes to the way linkdeath works with summoned items. Again, it's on my list. Hopefully after the holidays we'll be able to tackle my growing list…</B><P>

"Elemental Pets<BR>
--------------<BR>
Earth and Air: Nice! Thanks!"<BR><BR>

<B>Yer weclome.</B><P>

"Water: I wish I could say. Are you sure the drop has been fixed for 54 Water?"<BR><BR>

<B>So I have been told. But I haven't taken it off my list yet…</B><P>

"Fire: Argh! A 52 and 58 pet that casts low level spells, cancels debuffs, has a newbie fire shield, gates and can't melee to save its life or mine? Verant has told us that we just haven't found the right use for this pet. I'd bet I've logged more magician hours than ANY Verant staffer, but perhaps I'm just dumb. Please, please, please. Take a serious look at this pet! I don't know any magician who would take the current pet over the existing, properly buffed 49 and under pet model."<BR><BR>

<B>Also on my list.</B><P>

"Power of Pets: We've been told that our pets are more powerful than ever thanks to the DW bug fix a year ago. What Verant fails to mention is that fire, air and water now hit as slowly as earth. The differences in attack speed is now gone. Fire dished out more damage before, allowing it to finish fights faster than earth, now it doesn't. The differences in pets was narrowed greatly by this silent nerf. Just a point to make that pet variety got narrower. Narrower is bad."<BR><BR>

<B>Are you talking about the supposed 'nerf' that was supposed to have happened last week? I hate to repeat myself, but there wasn't one… The reduction of the procing will certainly make pets a bit weaker, even with the dual wielding change.</B><P>

"Decoy Pet<BR>
---------<BR>
This pet doesn't seem to be much of a decoy. As has been pointed out, it doesn't taunt very well. The whole point behind this pet is to get mobs to lock onto it! It should do that or it won't be useful."<P>

<B>On my list now (I'm sure you're tired of hearing that by now).</B><P>

"Rage of Zomm<BR>
------------<BR>
This pet is interesting. It's at least some variety, although I'm convinced that Zomm was a sissy mage that died at an early age. I wish this thing could survive more than a single ripostle. Would you consider increasing it's health? Give it half the health of an elemental. It is not dishing out twice as much damage as an elemental, so this would not seem to overpower the pet. If not, would you consider lowering the casting time to 2 seconds? Yes, 2 seconds. This would allow us a chance at summoning a pet to distract something that's beating us...even if not for very long."<BR><BR>

<B>Again, I'll bring it up. I'm not familiar with this pet, so I'll talk to someone about it.</B><P>

"Summoned Items<BR>
--------------<BR>
"Well, one man's junk..." is a newbie's dream? Nope. It's junk to most newbies too. The Sword of Runes is unqiue because of its proc. Other summons that proc that level of damage would be awesome! It'd give me options. I don't want to summon weapons that make warriors drool. What about weapons that proc a small DoT? Weapons whose proc is a serious taunt? Weapons that make wood elf women rain down from the sky?"<BR><BR>

<B>It may be a little while before we start talking about new procing summoned weapons. I'll certainly let you all know when we get to it, I'll probably ask for ideas.</B><P>

"Pet Heals<BR>
---------<BR>
I wish we had them when I was low enough for them to matter. They really added some dimension to the class. Why not give us a high level heal? I can resummon a pet in 10 - 12 seconds at 51+. Let me CH my own pet in 10 seconds for 500 mana. That's a lot of mana...more than a cleric's CH (and of course, limited to the pet). Now I have a choice. With 500 mana do I DD, try to summon a new pet or heal my own?"<BR><BR>

<B>Sounds interesting. Again, it's on my list… (yikes) </B><P>

"Buffs & Stuff<BR>
-------------<BR>
Invisibility: Why didn't magicians get improved invisibility? Normally, we get what other casters get with the exception of things like root and stun for which we must rely on pets. However, my pets don't invis me (thankfully, since they'd become despondent and suicide)."<BR><BR>

<B>Er… that's a Velious thing… but my answer would be, I don't know…</B><P>

"Phantom Armor: Woot! Finally, a reason for casting it! Now, two things...can you make it use one of something 4 times as expensive as the agate? No? What about one of something 10 times as expensive? I'd prefer that...most magicians 51+ would. Also, why does Sheild of Words overwrite this? If you can't let me have both my Phantom Armor and the cleric Shield of Words, then make Phantom Armor higher on the list so the cleric gets "Your spell did not take hold" -- I hate losing my armor to well meaning clerics."<P>

<B>You mean you want it to cost more? I don't know the current cost, so perhaps you're being sarcastic (and I hate missing good sarcasm… :) Again, I'll ask about the stacking on this spell, and the cost, once I figure out what you mean…</B><P>

"Epic Quest<BR>
----------<BR>
I need a no drop rare from the Minions of Hate? Ack! The "minion" is an 8-day timed spawn. He'll pop 45 times in a year (slightly more due to servers going down and resetting the timer). The general consensus is that the staff is dropped about 10% of the time. Ouch. Even if I can raise an army and get this minion every time, it will take between 8 and 80 days with the average being in the middle of that just to get this one item. Note the NPC says "minions of Hate" ... was the drop to be moved from where it is to the minions of its current owner?"<P>

<B>I've mentioned this elsewhere. The 'minions' thing is in there in anticipation of possible changes to Hate. Even when (if) it is changed, the minions will not be easier to deal with than the current holder of the item.</B><P>

"I need burning embers from a notable member of wurm kind? Well, eventually this will be found. I hope this really is dropping. There are a lot of people looking for it."<P>

<B>I hope so too…</B><P>

"In Closing<BR>
----------<BR>
I hope you understand that people like me make posts like this because we care about the game. We enjoy playing it and truly want to improve it. I don't want to become Uber. If I did, I'd go back to playing any number of games I can walk all over."<P>

<B>I do understand. We are all aware that if you really hated the game you wouldn't even be posting here, you'd be playing elsewhere. And I appreciate your feedback. I'm sorry that so many of your suggestions are on my 'list'. I know that sounds like a put-off, and it is kind of. But I will talk with people about these issues. You'll just have to be very patient about it… I hope that doesn't offend you.<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/036680.html">You have to be kidding me. Corpse dragging is instant argo in some SoV zones?</a></B><P>

How about a weeeeeeeeeeeeeeeeee bit more info. Will Rogues hide / sneak be broken while pulling bodies? Will regular invis disappear? Are you prepared to tell a player that looses everything that he spent months if not years getting that "Sorry, there is nothing I can do" if he cant get a Corpse summoned or pulled out? 
Just what are the limits?<P>

<B>Ok, here's a bit more information.<P>

The idea is that there are some places where, with a good faction, characters can travel unharmed. Some of those places are very, very dangerous to those that are not aligned with the folks that live there. These will be major adventuring/hunting zones for those that don’t mind not being able to wander around free there and talk to the locals.<P>

We really like it that way, but setting things up like that leads to a simple problem. Folks that are hated by the natives can make assaults on them and have their 'friends' who are well liked by the locals simply drag their corpses to safety, right in front of the people they were trying to kill. There are other potential abuses of this situation that I won't describe…<P>

So, to maintain the risk of fighting in these difficult places, we had to have these mobs get upset when you drag their kills off. And, yes, rogues and invisible types will have to be a lot more careful doing their recoveries once they actually lift that corpse up on their shoulders and start to scamper away.<P>

You will not have a problem dragging your own corpse (at least not any more of a problem than you would normally have). So if you accidentally fall to your death and you are friendly with the natives, you will be able to drag your own corpse all over the zone with no additional problems. But then, you won't need a safe spot either…<P>

This will make corpse recovery a little bit more difficult in the few places where this rule is used. But we see this as a necessary and useful inclusion. We wanted to tell you about it before hand to help reduce the number of people surprised by this addition.<P>

Alan<P>

Yikes!<P>

Correction on my last post.<P>

Dragging a corpse will not make you more visible. So if the creature sees through invis, it will still see you dragging a corpse. If it does not, dragging a corpse will not increase your visibility to that creature.<P>

Sorry for the goof on that. Hopefully I caught it fast enough.<P>

Alan</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

Axterix wrote: "Absor:
Let's say that Joe and myself, who are both friendly with the things in the dungeon, are going about our business. Joe takes a nice 10k plunge off a cliff. I go air elemental and float down to his body.<P>

Joe isn't KoS. I'm not KoS. Can I drag his body safely?<P>

Basically, you've stated that you can drag your own body around with no additional risk... what I want to know is does it merely look at if the body is yours or not or at the factions of the owner of the body?"<P>

<B>Normally we don't like to go into too much detail about stuff like this. But this works differently than people are used to, and we don’t want there to be too much confusion over this. You're right in your assumption. Dragging any corpse but your own will cause a reaction in those around you. Corpses don't have faction… So your friend will have to walk back and get his own corpse. </B><P>


Feydakin said: "I think this is the heart of the debate:
Is dragging a hated corpse a "faction hit" or does it just put you on a mob's hate list and cause it to attack. It is understood that if you are attacked and defeat the mob, you would take a faction hit. But the question that I'm seeing asked and not answered is whether you take and actual FACTION HIT by merely dragging a corpse.<P>

Can I, for instance, have good faction, but hightail it to the zone, dragging my buddy's corpse, and assuming I zone safely... have I lost faction with the pursuing mobs, or does zoning clean the hate list and I'm back to being best pals with them when I zone back over?"<P>

<B>There is no faction hit for dragging a corpse. You can do exactly as you suggest in your last paragraph with no loss of faction. And I'd consider you a brave and foolish friend for doing so. <P>

Alan</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
